description: Cognate with Saterland Frisian leeter (“later”), West Frisian letter (“later”), Dutch later (“later”), German Low German later (“later”).

entries.meaning: comparative form of late: more late
Coming afterward in time (used with than when comparing with another time).
examples: The Victorian era is a later period of English history than the Elizabethan era.

entries.meaning: Coming afterward in distance (following an antecedent distance as embedded within an adverbial phrase)
examples: I felt some leg pain during the first mile of my run and I strained my calf two miles later .

entries.meaning: At some time in the future.
examples: The meeting was adjourned to a later date.

adverbs.description: Cognate with Saterland Frisian leeter (“later”), West Frisian letter (“later”), Dutch later (“later”), German Low German later (“later”).

entries.meaning: comparative form of late: more late
examples: You came in late yesterday and today you came in even later.

entries.meaning: Afterward in time (used with than when comparing with another time).
examples: My roommate arrived first. I arrived later.
I arrived later than my roommate.

entries.meaning: At some unspecified time in the future.
examples: I wanted to do it now, but I’ll have to do it later.
